The paragraph from DORA that is most closely related to the BAIT article 5.2 is paragraph 6(1) of Article 11 of the Regulation (EU) 2019/1303 of the European Parliament and of the Council of 27 February 2019 on the European Union Agency for Cybersecurity (ENISA) and on the European Union Agency for Cybersecurity (ESA), which states that financial entities shall implement an ICT risk management framework that includes the following elements:

(a) a risk-based approach to network and infrastructure management, including the use of appropriate techniques, methods and protocols that may include implementing automation mechanisms to isolate affected information assets in the event of cyber attacks;

(b) policies that limit physical or logical access to information assets and ICT assets to what is required for legitimate and approved functions and activities only, and establish appropriate policies, procedures and controls that address access rights and ensure a sound administration thereof;

(c) policies and protocols for strong authentication mechanisms, based on relevant standards and dedicated control system, and protection measures of cryptographic keys whereby data is encrypted based on results of approved data classification and ICT risk assessment processes;

(d) policies and procedures for ICT change management, including changes to software, hardware, firmware components, systems or secur ity parameters, that are based on a risk assessment approach and are an integral part of the financial entity’s overall change management process, in order to ensure that all changes to ICT systems are recorded, tested, assessed, approved, implemented and verified in a controlled manner;

(e) policies and procedures for patches and updates.

